[1]
Date: Thu 01 Apr 2010
From: Peter Esko
<pesko@suddenlink.net>


Subject: Raptor Droppings
-------------------------
Regarding Promed Digest V2010 #137, "Avian influenza, poultry vs
migratory birds - Bulgaria:" The Moderator states that "Buzzards ...
can play their potential epidemiological role by dropping their
(infected) droppings while flying above (susceptible) poultry
premises. And they can repeat this stunt above additional premises
along their route."

Bird species vary in their defecation habits. Since raptors tend to
defecate predominately while roosting (including during or after
eating), there is little likelihood that even one domestic flock might
become infected from raptor droppings released in-flight. (Ducks and
geese tend to defecate where they walk or swim; this may be one reason
why they are such effective vectors for avian influenza. Seed-eating
songbirds defecate in flight, making them excellent vectors for seed
distribution.)

--
Peter Esko
<pesko@suddenlink.net>

[Having collected turkey buzzard faecal droppings under a roost, I can
but agree. - Mod.MHJ]

