[2]
Date: Thu 1 Apr 2010
From: Les Sims
<vetpath00@yahoo.com.au>


Re: Poultry versus Migratory Birds, Ref 20100331.1022
-----------------------------------------------------
There should no longer be a need to reopen the debate on the role of
poultry versus wild birds. It was largely settled in 2005 when the 1st
wild bird cases occurred in Mongolia in places largely devoid of
poultry.

Both trade in poultry and wild birds play a role in transmission of
highly pathogenic avian influenza viruses of the H5N1 subtype, with
wild birds almost certainly playing a much greater role in long
distance transcontinental / transoceanic) spread than poultry trade
over the past 5 years. The available genetic and epidemiological
evidence points strongly to wild bird introductions of Clade 2.2
viruses to Europe and Africa in 2005-06, to Japan and the Republic of
Korea in 2006-07. Clade 2.3.2 viruses were introduced to the Republic
of Korea and far Eastern Russia in 2008, and Mongolia and Russia in
2009, with the 2009 cases following a similar pattern of spread to
Clade 2.2 viruses in 2005. Unfortunately genetic data on wild bird
cases in Qinghai, China from 2009 that preceded the Russian and
Mongolian cases are not yet available in the public arena.

What is more interesting is the apparent absence of new Clade 2.2
cases over the past 12 months in wild birds or in places currently
free from infection visited by migratory birds. This finding suggests
that an independent cycle of transmission in wild birds with Clade 2.2
viruses has not been sustained in northern Asia and Europe. The only
wild bird isolates in public databases from north of China in the past
12 months are Clade 2.3.2 viruses.

--
L.D. Sims
Asia Pacific Veterinary Information Services
PO Box 344
Palm Cove Qld 4879
Australia
<vetpath00@yahoo.com.au>

[Les Sims, a veterinary consultant, co-authored with Clare Narrod, an
economist, FAO's comprehensive document "Understanding avian
influenza" -- a "review of the emergence, spread, control, prevention
and effects of Asian-lineage H5N1 highly pathogenic viruses." Its 1st
installment includes Chapter 1, "Introduction" (4 pp); Chapter 2,
"Current state of knowledge on HPAI" (15pp); Chapter 3, "H5N1 HPAI in
different species" (15 pp); and bibliography (16 pp).

The preface says: "Understanding avian influenza explores the various
mechanisms of persistence and spread of H5N1 HPAI viruses -- both
confirmed and possible -- in order to understand better the sources of
virus and the modes of transmission. It does this in an effort to
separate science from perception, and to highlight areas where
uncertainty remains."

Key areas discussed include the role played by domestic ducks in the
development of the current epizootic, issues related to whether the
disease emerged from intensively-reared poultry, and the relative role
of wild birds and trade in poultry in disease spread.

Subscribers are encouraged to visit this well-documented review at
<http://www.fao.org/avianflu/documents/key_ai/key_book_preface.htm>.
- Mod.AS]

[Members are strongly recommended to read this document. But there is
an interesting paragraph in the 2.6 Conclusions in Chapter 2:

"Asian-lineage H5N1 HPAI viruses have now spread across 3 continents.
The mode of spread of these viruses is still not entirely clear. Trade
in poultry and poultry products and movement of wild birds have played
a role, although the relative contributions of these in the initial
introduction into countries previously free from infection has not
always been determined. Much of the evidence supporting these various
modes of introduction is circumstantial and complicated in many cases
by failure to detect the initial incursion of virus. Molecular
epidemiology has assisted greatly in assessing links between various
isolates."

And they should look out for the 'Conclusions and Recommendations' of
the Scientific Task Force on Avian Influenza and Wild Birds, Third
Technical Meeting on 15-16 Mar 2010. - Mod.MHJ]

